PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F346A1673045701
OL,6,FThe following night, more surprisingly,
OL,7,FA Question of Sport took the 6.30pm
OL,8,Fslot. On both days, the One and Ten ran
OL,9,Fto their usual lengths.
OL,11,FThe exact reasoning seems unclear. On
OL,12,Fboth occasions, the full news hour
OL,13,Fwould have been likely to get more
OL,14,Fviewers.
OL,16,FResourcing or holiday leave Is unlikely
OL,17,Fto have been the issue ` at least for
OL,18,Fnetwork and the nations.
OL,3,CTime to rethink the Christmas
OL,4,Ccurtailing of BBC One news?
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G2/7
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34603
SC,0003
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F346A1673045701
OL,6,FBut a look back at the schedules
OL,7,Freveals that the BBC has form in this
OL,8,Ffrom decades ago.
OL,10,FOn Friday 20th December 1974 there was
OL,11,Fno Nine o'Clock News. A shortened
OL,12,Fbulletin was shown at 9.15pm. The
OL,13,Freason? It seems a repeat of The
OL,14,FGoodies and Ken Dodd's World of
OL,15,FLaughter was more in keeping with the
OL,16,Fholiday mood.
OL,18,FFast forward to 1978. Of course, BBC TV
OL,19,Fwas blacked out for several days before
OL,20,FChristmas that year but the planned
OL,21,Fschedule for 22nd December was unusual.
OL,3,CTime to rethink the Christmas
OL,4,Ccurtailing of BBC One news?
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S      G3/7
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
